    <question>
        <prompt>Alfred E. Smith's 1928 presidential campaign faced opposition due to his:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Foreign policy positions</option>
            <option letter="b">Catholicism and anti-Prohibition stance</option>
            <option letter="c">Economic policies</option>
            <option letter="d">Support for immigration</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Alfred E. Smith's 1928 campaign faced significant opposition primarily because he was Catholic and opposed Prohibition. His Catholicism sparked anti-Catholic prejudice, particularly in rural Protestant areas, while his "wet" stance on Prohibition alienated supporters of temperance. His urban background and cultural identity as a New Yorker also contributed to his decisive loss to Herbert Hoover.</explanation>
    </question>
